</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1158BBC73F1753A7075774AC76E2AEEB" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" type="description">
<paragraph id="BD62F14D7617002722F9512ABECC9E34" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BBA97795C5031A3530666C9F7BA6104D" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
Annual with adventious root; stems 5-25 cm long from central rootstock, decumbent, indumentum of scattered long hairs mixed with some shorter pubescence. Leaves 1-5 
<normalizedToken id="8469092594F63C383FD200D3E2C556D3" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.2-0.6 cm, oblong-oblanceolate; apex rounded; base attenuate, petiole-like, margin entire. Flowers solitary, axilary; peduncles 0.8-1.6 cm, often becoming recurved in fruit; bracteoles 3-6 (-9) 
<normalizedToken id="B213ABAEB0CE0D723F3AD7BE4CDB6436" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-2 mm, oblanceolate; pedicels 1-3 mm; outer sepals 5 
<normalizedToken id="A451EB40D8E89B2805C5A5566B83B40C" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1 mm, lanceolate-oblong, acute to apiculate, differing from the oblong-obovate inner sepals; corolla 5-6 mm long, deeply lobed, pale blue with white midpetaline bands radiating from the centre; midpetaline bands glabrous, terminating in a mucro; filaments eglandular; ovary glabrous; style glabrous, divided 1-1.5 mm above base, stigmas 1 mm. Capsule glabrous; seeds tuberculate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3260B4973D793299373C78716B8A61E3" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2475A2C8852DD19201C65C27A5337526" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FCCC3D4DEC0E6685AAD7FA3D484E0287" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
United States of America: California (
<emphasis id="8D6D848E854B261972B7B1B96CBC16E2" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Greene</emphasis>
1665, 
<emphasis id="A8D14A90E1CC2010F2583644154B040E" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Pringle</emphasis>
s.n. [6/4/1882]), Arizona (fide 
<bibRefCitation id="4FCFD58F98D0E7769C77EC141CDCEE06" author="Austin, DF" journalOrPublisher="Canotia" pageId="198" pageNumber="199" pagination="79 - 106" refId="B12" refString="Austin, DF, 2006. Noteworthy distributions and additions in Southwestern Convolvulaceae. Canotia 2 (3): 79 - 106" title="Noteworthy distributions and additions in Southwestern Convolvulaceae." volume="2" year="2006">Austin 2006</bibRefCitation>
: 79); Mexico: Baja California (
<emphasis id="8AC5EEA5E1BB21061C76AFFC4F0F6C2F" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Raven et al.</emphasis>
12670).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6905218F205A2CDF8B00D7501FD66B6B" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" type="notes">
<paragraph id="4DA7C9CE6B10E9DBA0CF3E8CBF969B02" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A54008BAC0C5422A081670E59BB63388" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
Although separated geographically from related species, 
<taxonomicName id="F11EB5AB42E13AAD798E17A49D5988D9" authorityName="L. M. Perry, Rhodora 33: 76. 1931. (Perry" authorityYear="1931" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus simulans" order="Solanales" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="simulans">
<emphasis id="5C21E74EDA78CA09AD784E29B5BBD444" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Convolvulus simulans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very close to 
<taxonomicName id="8F51DC6BE5EE2A6DA2108A2319D3EAE3" authorityName="L., Syst. Nat. ed. 12, 3: 229. 1768. (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1768" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus pentapetaloides" order="Solanales" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pentapetaloides">
<emphasis id="BC79B32F3A028EE0F8F7F50328299A70" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Convolvulus pentapetaloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its allies morphologically and this is confirmed by our molecular studies which show they all belong to a single clade (
<bibRefCitation id="3720232843BA2AE945970AF18CC0D7A6" author="Williams, BRM" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="214" pageNumber="215" pagination="1287 - 1306" publicationUrl="10.12705/636.9" refId="B388" refString="Williams, BRM, Mitchell, TC, Wood, JRI, Harris, DJ, Scotland, RW, Carine, MA, 2014. Integrating DNA barcode data in a monograph of Convolvulus L. Taxon 63: 1287 - 1306, DOI: 10.12705/636.9" title="Integrating DNA barcode data in a monograph of Convolvulus L." url="10.12705/636.9" volume="63" year="2014">Williams et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
